== Town commissioners == {{main|Town commissioners}} Many of the extinguished boroughs had an additional form of local government in place, in the form of commissioners appointed under the Lighting of Towns (Ireland) Act, 1828. Where such a body existed, it was deemed to be the successor to the corporation. Section 16 of the Act provided that any borough dissolved with property worth more than £100, and which did not have commissioners under the 1828 Act, should have a board of "Municipal Commissioners" established. In most cases, the commissioners appointed under the terms of the 1840 Act eventually adopted the terms of the 1828 Act or its replacement, the Towns Improvement (Ireland) Act 1854. By 1876, only Carrickfergus was still governed by commissioners appointed under the 1840 Act.<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.dippam.ac.uk/eppi/documents/16178/page/425552|title=Report and proceedings |author=Select Committee on Local government and taxation of towns (Ireland) |date=11 July 1876 |page=3 §15 |accessdate=26 November 2014 |series=[[Command paper]]s |volume=C.352}}</ref>
